"use strict";(self.webpackChunklotrwiki=self.webpackChunklotrwiki||[]).push([[277],{4656:function(e,t,a){a.r(t),a.d(t,{Head:function(){return i}});var r=a(7294),n=a(1883),s=a(4842),l=a(3522);t.default=()=>r.createElement(s.Z,{title:"Rules"},r.createElement("h1",null,"Rules"),r.createElement("hr",null),r.createElement("p",null,"The world of Middle Earth is a very different sort of world to the more common worldtypes D&D is played in, such as the ones described in the official source books. Mostly because absolute good and evil exist, and magic takes a very different form. As such, we are using a few optional rules from the DMG, as well as a bunch of homebrew table rules and mechanics. These make combat more interesting, and compensate for the otherwise-grity combo of no magical healing and rare long rests within the Adventures in Middle Earth system."),r.createElement(l.z,{hideWhenSmall:!0,pageTitle:"Rules",links:[{name:"Combat Rules",url:"/rules#combatrules"},{name:"Skill Check Successes",url:"/rules#skillchecks"},{name:"Exhaustion",url:"/rules#exhaustion"}]}),r.createElement("p",{className:"tmargin"},"Note: Some mechanics require more involved descriptions, and as such get their own pages. Namely, these are the ",r.createElement(n.Link,{to:"/calendar"},"Calendar")," and ",r.createElement(n.Link,{to:"/weather"},"Weather")," pages."),r.createElement("hr",null),r.createElement("h3",{id:"combatrules"},"Combat Rules"),r.createElement("p",null,"These rules come mostly from the Dungeon Master's Workshop at the back of the ",r.createElement("a",{href:"https://www.dndbeyond.com/sources/dmg/dungeon-masters-workshop",target:"_blank"},"DMG"),". Some of them have been modified slightly to better fit our table. ",r.createElement("br",null),r.createElement("br",null),"Listed here: Healing Surges, Climb onto a Bigger Creature, Disarm, Shove Aside, Overrun/Tumble, and Reduced to 0 HP. ",r.createElement("br",null)),r.createElement("h5",null,"Healing Surges"),r.createElement("p",null,"As an action, a character can use a healing surge and spend up to half their Hit Dice. The player can decide to spend an additional Hit Dice after each roll (up to half their level rounded down). A character who uses a healing surge can't do so again until they finish a short or long rest. ",r.createElement("br",null),r.createElement("br",null),"Under this optional rule, a character regains all spent Hit Dice at the end of a long rest. With a short rest, a character regains Hit Dice equal to his or her level divided by four (minimum of one die)."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Climb onto a Bigger Creature"),r.createElement("p",null,"If one creature wants to jump onto another creature, it can do so by grappling. A Small or Medium creature has little chance of making a successful grapple against a Huge or Gargantuan creature, however. As an alternative, a suitably large opponent can be treated as terrain for the purpose of jumping onto its back or clinging to a limb. After making any ability checks necessary to get into position and onto the larger creature, the smaller creature uses its action to make a Strength (Athletics) or Dexterity (Acrobatics) check contested by the target's Dexterity (Acrobatics) check. If it wins the contest, the smaller creature successfully moves into the target creature's space and clings to its body. ",r.createElement("br",null),"While in the target's space, the smaller creature moves with the target and has advantage on attack rolls against it. ",r.createElement("br",null),r.createElement("br",null),"The smaller creature can move around within the larger creature's space, treating the space as difficult terrain. The larger creature's ability to attack the smaller creature depends on the smaller creature's location, and is left to your discretion. The larger creature can dislodge the smaller creature as an action—knocking it off, scraping it against a wall, or grabbing and throwing it—by making a Strength (Athletics) check contested by the smaller creature's Strength (Athletics) or Dexterity (Acrobatics) check. The smaller creature chooses which ability to use."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Disarm"),r.createElement("p",null,"A creature can use a weapon attack to knock a weapon or another item from a target's grasp. The attacker makes an attack roll contested by the target's Strength (Athletics) check or Dexterity (Acrobatics) check. If the attacker wins the contest, the attack causes no damage or other ill effect, but the defender drops the item. ",r.createElement("br",null)," ",r.createElement("br",null),"The attacker has disadvantage on its attack roll if the target is holding the item with two or more hands. The target has advantage on its ability check if it is larger than the attacking creature, or disadvantage if it is smaller."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Shove Aside"),r.createElement("p",null,"With this option, a creature uses the special shove attack from the Player's Handbook to force a target to the side, rather than away. The attacker has disadvantage on its Strength (Athletics) check when it does so. If that check is successful, the attacker moves the target 5 feet to a different space within its reach."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Overrun/Tumble"),r.createElement("p",null,"A creature can try to run through a hostile creature's space. As an action, the mover can either attempt to force its way through by overrunning the creature, or can try to tumble through by ducking and weaving past it. The mover must make a contested Strength (Athletics) check or Dexterity (Acrobatics) check. If the mover wins, it can move through the hostile creature's space once this turn. This does provoke opportunity attacks as normal."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Reduced to 0 HP"),r.createElement("p",null,"Being reduced to 0 hit points is a harrowing experience. If a character is reduced to 0 hit points (in combat or out of it), they must make a DC 15 Corruption saving throw against 1 shadow point. Additionally, they gain 1 level of exhaustion."),r.createElement("hr",null),r.createElement("h3",{id:"skillchecks"},"Skill Check Successes"),r.createElement("p",null,"Once more, the lack of direct magic can sometimes make things a little repetitive. Plus the question arises: If there are no spells, then how does the ambient magic of Middle Earth come into play? My answer, at least in part, is to use skill check success effects. ",r.createElement("br",null),"If a player character more than succeeds on a skill check they are proficient in, they can trigger an effect. Different effects have different requirements and costs. ",r.createElement("br",null),r.createElement("br",null),"Note: most do not trigger necessarily on a natural 20, but on a roll of more than x. This reduces the likelihood of the scenario where someone with a -3 modifier to a skill somehow outdoes the other character with expertise who just rolled badly."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Inspire"),r.createElement("p",null,"Requirement: 20+ ",r.createElement("br",null),"Describe how your success is inspiring to others. They must be able to hear, see, or otherwise detect your success. Allied creatures who hear/see/detect your success and with whom your description resonates gain inspiration."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Lose Shadow Point"),r.createElement("p",null,"Requirement: 25+ ",r.createElement("br",null),"Describe how your success encourages your spirit and makes you feel that good will ultimately triumph. Remove 1 temporary shadow point."),r.createElement("h5",null,"Magical Effect"),r.createElement("p",null,"Requirement: 25+, or 20+ with a Wondrous Artefact. ",r.createElement("br",null),'You may declare that you wish to spend Inspiration and a variable number of Hit Dice in order to succeed at something "impossible" by turning a successful skill check into a Magical Result. A Magical Result indicates that the outcome of the task not only surpassed all expectations but achieved something beyond your normal capabilities - in other words, a feat that could hardly be accomplished without magical aid. If you were not using a Wondrous Artefact, then you may trigger the effect, but the DM decides the outcome.'),r.createElement("hr",null),r.createElement("h3",{id:"exhaustion"},"Exhaustion"),r.createElement("p",null,"The exhaustion system is very important in this sort of low-magic campaign where things such as the serious injuries from the back of the DMG would be too debilitating due to the lack of magical healing. The sparsity of long rests also means that it narratively makes sense. But the 5E exhaustion system is fairly debilitating. In order to use the exhaustion system to indicate weariness without making the game less fun for players, we are implementing a modified form of the One D&D exhaustion rules. ",r.createElement("br",null)," ",r.createElement("br",null),"Exhaustion is cumulative. There are 10 levels of exhaustion, and a character dies if they hit the 10th level. Whenever an exhausted character makes a d20 roll, they subtract their exhaustion level from the result."));const i=()=>r.createElement("title",null,"Rules")}}]);
